track_notes: From the Bighorn Falls trailhead, go directly up the hill to the large grassy meadows.  Follow horse tracks across the meadows in the direction of Evangaline Peak.  At one point you will come to a junction to either Poplar Ridge or Evangaline Peak, follow the trail to Evangaline Peak and leave the trail in an area that has been logged in the past.  From this point it is bushwacking, following the ridge to the treeline.  At the treeline you will enter an alpine meadow which will transition to a shale covered ridge for a straighforward approach to the summit.  Cell reception is unreliable and should not be depended upon.

Evangeline Peak is a pretty gentle hike and you may be tempted to traverse to Eagle N1, also known as Poplar Peak and Rum Ridge.  It involves some pretty easy scrambling but it is long and requires good route finding abilities.  Just follow the ridge all the way to Poplar Peak, navigating over, around or through several (about 10) gendarmes dropping off Evangeline, and accessing Poplar Ridge.  From the summit of Poplar Peak (Eagle N1), there are a few more gendarmes to navigate.  You lose a lot of elevation to gain Eagle N1 and there are a lot of ups and downs to make the traverse.  By the summit of Eagle N1 (Poplar Peak), you will have gained over 1,500 meters.  This route has been graded SC6, YDS-3.
track_title: Evangeline-Eagle N1 or Poplar Ridge Traverse
